://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299\", \"benchmark_dataset_split\": \"all\", \"document_type\": \"newspaper\", \"date\": \"1898\", \"language\": \"en\", \"publication_title\": \"The Sydney Morn aid\", \"transcription_unit_scope\": \"article\", \"segmentation_origin_article\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_lines\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_sentences\": \"benchmark - automatic\"}, \"ground_truth\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"CENTRAL CRIMINAL COURT.\\n(Before Mr. Justice Owen.)\\nMr. C. G. Wade was Crown Prosecutor.\\nSENTENCES.\\nHis Honor passed the following sentences:- Wil¬\\nliam Henry Williams, who had pleaded guilty to\\nbigamy, was sent to gaol for l8 months ; William\\nDavis and Alfred Drury, found guilty of assault\\nand robbery, were each sentenced to three years' im¬\\nprisonment.\\nA CASE POSTPONED.\\nThe trial of George Wells and Walter Townsend\\nwas postponed until the next Court, Mr C. Bull,\\nwho appeared for Townsend, having made applica¬\\ntion for a postponement. The accused were ar¬\\nraigned upon a charge of assault and robbery.\\nA CHARGE OF ARSON.\\nDaniel Joseph Kelleher pleaded not guilty when\\narraigned upon an indictment charging him with\\nhaving, on August 14, maliciously set fire to his shop\\nwith intent to defraud. Mr Niland appeared for\\nthe defence. The accused was convicted and re¬\\nmanded for sentence.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 23], [24, 50], [51, 87], [88, 98], [99, 146], [147, 193], [194, 242], [243, 290], [291, 343], [344, 355], [356, 373], [374, 419], [420, 467], [468, 515], [516, 561], [562, 607], [608, 626], [627, 673], [674, 720], [721, 775], [776, 822], [823, 869], [870, 890]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 23], [24, 50], [51, 87], [88, 98], [99, 355], [356, 373], [374, 540], [541, 607], [608, 626], [627, 799], [800, 835], [836, 890]], \"num_tokens\": 126, \"num_chars\": 890, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.93}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"CEN