nbinding on the tributers. The men do not\\napprove of the terms offered by the tributers,\\nbut the whole of the position is under con¬\\nsideration.\\nThe Hebburn colliery horses were brought\\nfrom the company's paddock to Hebburn to¬\\nday.\\nThe management of the Pelaw-Main Colliery\\nhave declined to consider the proposals made\\nby the employees for increased pay in certain\\nportions of the mine, alleged to be very wet.\\nThe matter will be referred to the district\\nboard.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 28], [29, 49], [50, 92], [93, 132], [133, 178], [179, 218], [219, 257], [258, 303], [304, 348], [349, 393], [394, 438], [439, 483], [484, 530], [531, 580], [581, 618], [619, 659], [660, 705], [706, 746], [747, 793], [794, 837], [838, 849], [850, 890], [891, 932], [45, 49], [938, 979], [980, 1024], [1025, 1070], [1071, 1116], [1117, 1160], [1161, 1167]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 28], [29, 49], [50, 228], [229, 731], [732, 849], [850, 937], [938, 1116], [1117, 1167]], \"num_tokens\": 178, \"num_chars\": 1167, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.97}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"I KURRI KURRI LABOUR TROUBLES. I\\nKURRI KURRI, Sunday.\\nThe Hebburn miners, who aro out on strike,\\nthough they deprecate the uso of such a\\nterm, are using stringent measures to enforce\\nattendance of all members at the weekly\\nmeetings. Hopes aro entertained that a\\nsettlement will bo arrived at, In view of the\\nmino being taken on tribute by Messrs. Ralph\\nTurnbull and H. Savage, who havo offered tho\\nfollowing terms to the men:-10s 6d per day\\nfor Bhooters down, with powder supplied free\\nof charge, and a bonus of 2}d per ton to each\\nshooter for every ton over 56; fillers to receive\\n8d per ton; all tho arrangements made\\nbetween tho men and the company previous\\nto tho troublo regarding deficient work to be\\nbinding on the tributers. Tho men do not\\napprove of tho terms offered by the trlbutors,\\nbut tho whole o£ tho position is under con\\nSllliTttlinn.\\nTho Hobbur.i colliery horses were brought\\nfrom tho company's paddock to Hebburn to-\\nday.\\nThe management of the Polaw-Main Colliery\\nhave declined to consider the proposals mado\\nby the employees for increased pay In cortaln\\nportions of tho mino, alleged to bo vory wet.\\nThe matter will be referred to tho district\\nboard.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 32], [33, 53], [54, 96], [97, 136], [137, 182], [183, 222], [223, 261], [262, 307], [308, 352], [353, 397], [398, 440], [441, 485], [486, 531], [532, 581], [582, 619], [620, 660], [661, 706], [707, 747], [748, 794], [795, 837], [838, 851], [852, 893], [894, 935], [49, 53], [941, 982], [983, 1027], [1028, 1073], [1074, 1119], [1120, 1163], [1164, 1170]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 30], [31, 53], [54, 232], [233, 732], [733, 851], [852, 940], [941, 1119], [1120, 1170]], \"num_tokens\": 177, \"num_chars\": 1170, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.95, \"cer\": 0.046272, \"wer\": 0.224719, \"nb_char_substitutions\": 43, \"nb_char_deletions\": 4, \"nb_char_insertions\": 7}}, \"ocr_postcorrection_output\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"None\", \"ocr_postcorrection_system\": \"None\", \"num_tokens\": -1, \"num_chars\": -1, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": -1, \"cer\": -1, \"wer\": -1, \"nb_char_substitutions\": -1, \"nb_char_deletions\": -1, \"nb_char_insertions\": -1}}}","{\"document_metadata\": {\"document_id\": \"14849000\", \"primary_dataset_name\": \"overproof-combined\", \"primary_dataset_filename\": \"data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt\", \"primary_dataset_version\": \"v1.0\", \"primary_dataset_license\": \"Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.\", \"primary_dataset_url\": \"https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation\", \"benchmark_dataset_name\": \"hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof\", \"benchmark_dataset_doi\": \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299\", \"benchmark_dataset_split\": \"all\", \"document_type\": \"newspaper\", \"date\": \"1907\", \"language\": \"en\", \"publication_title\": \"The Sydney Morn aid\", \"transcription_unit_scope\": \"article\", \"segmentation_origin_article\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_lines\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_sentences\": \"benchmark - automatic\"}, \"ground_truth\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"SYDNEY QUARTER SESSIONS.\\n(Before Judge Backhouse and juries.)\\nMr Herbert Harris prosecuted for the\\nCrown.\\nALLEGED THEFT.\\nAlfred Clark a kitcheman was charged\\nwith stealing a quantity of clothing, a fish\\nfork and a saucepan, the property of Agnes\\nIda Smith He was further charged with\\nhaving the property mentioned in his pos¬\\nsession, well knowing it to have been stolen.\\nThe evidence showed that the accused was\\nemployed by the prosecutrix, who keeps a\\nboarding-house in Macleay-street. On De¬\\ncember 22 he left his place and that night he\\nwas arrested by Senior Constable Lonsdale\\nand taken to where he was lodging. On the\\npolice wanting to search his room the ac¬\\ncused resisted their efforts and violently\\nassaulted Constable Blair, for which he was\\nsentenced to six months' hard labour. Ow¬\\ning to his resistance the police were unable\\nto search the room, but the following morn¬\\ning they found the property mentioned in the\\ncharge there.\\nThe defence was a denial of any knowledge\\nof the stolen property, which the accused as¬\\nserted had been placed in his room to secure\\nhis conviction.\\nThe jury returned a verdict of not guilty\\non both counts, and the accused was dis¬\\ncharged.\\nRECEIVING STOLEN PROPERTY.\\nRobert John Carmichael pleaded guilty to a\\ncharge of receiving a coat, a pair of trou¬\\nsers, a vest, and a brooch, the property of\\nGeorge Sewell, well knowing the same to have\\nbeen stolen. He also pleaded guilty to a\\nsimilar charge in connection with a quantity\\nof clothing and cutlery, the property of Henry\\nM'Credie.\\nThe accused, who was defended by Mr. E. R.\\nAbigail, was remanded for sentence.\\nALLEGED FALSE PRETENCES.\\nRobert Millett and Mary Edith Millett, his\\nwife pleaded not guilty to a charge of false\\npretences. The indictment stated that on\\nOctober 9, 1906 the accused falsely pretended\\nto Hymen Lobel Friedman that Mary Edith\\nMillett had entered into a contract with\\nHenry Benjamin Pollard for the sale of cer¬\\ntain land to him for £2500, and that the sum\\nof £1500 had been lodged in cash as a de¬\\nposit in part payment by Pollard with George\\nMoffat Robinson, a conveyancer and that Pol¬\\nlard was a purchaser with money at his dis¬\\nposal to complete the purchase and did then\\nfalsely promise Friedman that Pollard would\\npay the balance of the purchase money and\\nby means of which promise the accused ob¬\\ntained from Friedman £50, with intent to do\\nfraud.\\nThere were two other counts in which the\\naccused were charged with obtaining by simi¬\\nlar representations from Friedman the sum\\nof £100 on October 12, and £200 on Oc¬\\ntober 22.\\nMr. J. C. Gannon instructed by Mr. W. E.\\nHawkins appeared for the accused.\\nHis Honor directed the jury to return a\\nverdict of not guilty against the female ac¬\\ncused and she was discharged. The male ac¬\\ncused was also found not guilty and acquit¬\\nted.\\nSENTENCES\\nThe following sentences were passed: - Wil¬\\nliam Morris breaking and entering two years'\\nhard labour, Charles Campbell, false pre¬\\nsences, one year and a day; Robert Anderson\\nindecent assault, three years' penal servi¬\\ntude.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 24], [25, 61], [62, 98], [99, 105], [106, 120], [121, 157], [158, 202], [203, 245], [246, 283], [284, 325], [326, 371], [372, 412], [413, 453], [454, 494], [495, 540], [541, 582], [583, 624], [625, 666], [667, 709], [710, 753], [754, 795], [796, 840], [841, 884], [885, 929], [930, 943], [944, 985], [986, 1031], [1032, 1076], [1077, 1