rienced players and promising youngsters,\\namong whom is a centre, J. M. Mowatt, who has\\nattracted the attention of discerning critics. Dr.\\nA. W. Ross, free from cricket, is again the full¬\\nback. St. George Is an unknown quantity, with\\nits strength probably in the forwards, led by inter¬\\nnational Bruce Judd.\\nUNIVERSITY FIT.\\nUniversity Is one team which will enter the\\nfield to-morrow fit to fight out a hard contest.\\nThe team meets Northern Suburbs at University\\nOval. University has pleased coach P. A. McCue,\\nand the forwards surprised many by the manner\\nin which they overcame the tactics of the big\\nManly pack In the last of the trial matches. Nor¬\\nthern Suburbs has made gains, among them being\\n\\\u0026quot;Waratah\\\u0026quot; Sid King, who, if a head injury has\\nsufficiently healed, will play at five eighth. Hem¬\\nmingway, University winger who toured New Zea¬\\nland as a member of the Australian team last year,\\nis another acquisition.\\nWestern Suburbs, a greatly altered team with\\nseveral promising players recruited form lower¬\\ngrade teams, Is to play its first few matches at\\nConcord Oval, formerly known as St. Luke\u0026#39;s Oval,\\nwhich has been considerably improved. Opposi¬\\ntion to morrow will be provided by the strong Drum¬\\nmoyne fifteen. Among those making a debut in\\nsenior football will be last year\u0026#39;s star St. Joseph\u0026#39;s\\nCollege and Great Public Schools\u0026#39; wing three¬\\nquarter, J. Kelaher, who is with Drummoyne.\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;line_offsets\u0026quot;: [[0, 9], [10, 22], [23, 43], [44, 65], [66, 115], [116, 160], [161, 213], [214, 258], [259, 306], [307, 353], [354, 399], [400, 448], [449, 498], [499, 545], [546, 591], [592, 640], [641, 691], [692, 737], [738, 790], [791, 833], [834, 839], [840, 883], [884, 929], [930, 974], [975, 1022], [1023, 1071], [1072, 1121], [1122, 1168], [1169, 1217], [1218, 1264], [1265, 1314], [1315, 1357], [1358, 1406], [1407, 1458], [1459, 1503], [1