<div id="LC7" class="react-code-text react-code-line-contents-no-virtualization react-file-line html-div ">{&quot;document_metadata&quot;: {&quot;document_id&quot;: &quot;14849000&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;overproof-combined&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_filename&quot;: &quot;data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_version&quot;: &quot;v1.0&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_license&quot;: &quot;Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_url&quot;: &quot;https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_doi&quot;: &quot;https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_split&quot;: &quot;all&quot;, &quot;document_type&quot;: &quot;newspaper&quot;, &quot;date&quot;: &quot;1907&quot;, &quot;language&quot;: &quot;en&quot;, &quot;publication_title&quot;: &quot;The Sydney Morn aid&quot;, &quot;transcription_unit_scope&quot;: &quot;article&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_article&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_lines&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_sentences&quot;: &quot;benchmark - automatic&quot;}, &quot;ground_truth&quot;: {&quot;transcription_unit&quot;: &quot;SYDNEY QUARTER SESSIONS.\n(Before Judge Backhouse and juries.)\nMr Herbert Harris prosecuted for the\nCrown.\nALLEGED THEFT.\nAlfred Clark a kitcheman was charged\nwith stealing a quantity of clothing, a fish\nfork and a saucepan, the property of Agnes\nIda Smith He was further charged with\nhaving the property mentioned in his pos¬\nsession, well knowing it to have been stolen.\nThe evidence showed that the accused was\nemployed by the prosecutrix, who keeps a\nboarding-house in Macleay-street. On De¬\ncember 22 he left his place and that night he\nwas arrested by Senior Constable Lonsdale\nand taken to where he was lodging. On the\npolice wanting to search his room the ac¬\ncused resisted their efforts and violently\nassaulted Constable Blair, for which he was\nsentenced to six months&#39; hard labour. Ow¬\ning to his resistance the police were unable\nto search the room, but the following morn¬\ning they found the property mentioned in the\ncharge there.\nThe defence was a denial of any knowledge\nof the stolen property, which the accused as¬\nserted had been placed in his room to secure\nhis conviction.\nThe jury returned a verdict of not guilty\non both counts, and the accused was dis¬\ncharged.\nRECEIVING STOLEN PROPERTY.\nRobert John Carmichael pleaded guilty to a\ncharge of receiving a coat, a pair of trou¬\nsers, a vest, and a brooch, the property of\nGeorge Sewell, well knowing the same to have\nbeen stolen. He also pleaded guilty to a\nsimilar charge in connection with a quantity\nof clothing and cutlery, the property of Henry\nM&#39;Credie.\nThe accused, who was defended by Mr. E. R.\nAbigail, was remanded for sentence.\nALLEGED FALSE PRETENCES.\nRobert Millett and Mary Edith Millett, his\nwife pleaded not guilty to a charge of false\npretences. The indictment stated that on\nOctober 9, 1906 the accused falsely pretended\nto Hymen Lobel Friedman that Mary Edith\nMillett had entered into a contract with\nHenry Benjamin Pollard for the sale of cer¬\ntain land to him for £2500, and that the sum\nof £1500 had been lodged in cash as a de¬\nposit in part payment by Pollard with George\nMoffat Robinson, a conveyancer and that Pol¬\nlard was a purchaser with money at his dis¬\nposal to complete the purchase and did then\nfalsely promise Friedman that Pollard would\npay the balance of the purchase money and\nby means of which promise the accused ob¬\ntained from Friedman £50, with intent to do\nfraud.\nThere were two other counts in which the\naccused were charged with obtaining by simi¬\nlar representations from Friedman the sum\nof £100 on October 12, and £200 on Oc¬\ntober 22.\nMr. J. C. Gannon instructed by Mr. W. E.\nHawkins appeared for the accused.\nHis Honor directed the jury to return a\nverdict of not guilty against the female ac¬\ncused and she was discharged. The male ac¬\ncused was also found not guilty and acquit¬\nted.\nSENTENCES\nThe following sentences were passed: - Wil¬\nliam Morris breaking and entering two years&#39;\nhard labour, Charles Campbell, false pre¬\nsences, one year and a day; Robert Anderson\nindecent assault, three years&#39; penal servi¬\ntude.&quot;, &quot;line_offsets&quot;: [[0, 24], [25, 61], [62, 98], [99, 105], [106, 120], [121, 157], [158, 202], [203, 245], [246, 283], [284, 325], [326, 371], [372, 412], [413, 453], [454, 494], [495, 540], [541, 582], [583, 624], [625, 666], [667, 709], [710, 753], [754, 795], [796, 840], [841, 884], [885, 929], [930, 943], [944, 985], [986, 1031], [1032, 1076], [1077, 1092], [1093, 1134], [1135, 1175], [1176, 1184], [1185, 1211], [1212, 1254], [1255, 1298], [1299, 1342], [1343, 1387], [1388, 1428], [1429, 1473], [1474, 1520], [1521, 1530], [1531, 1573], [1574, 1609], [1610, 1634], [1635, 1677], [1678, 1722], [1723, 1763], [1764, 1809], [1810, 1849], [1850, 1890], [1891, 1934], [1935, 1979], [1980, 2021], [2022, 2066], [2067, 2111], [2112, 2155], [2156, 2199], [2200, 2243], [2244, 2285], [2286, 2327], [2328, 2371], [2372, 2378], [2379, 2419], [2420, 2464], [2465, 2506], [2507, 2545], [2546, 2555], [2556, 2596], [2597, 2630], [2631, 2670], [2671, 2715], [2716, 2758], [2759, 2802], [2803, 2807], [2808, 2817], [2818, 2861], [2862, 2906], [2907, 2948], [2949, 2992], [2993, 3036], [3037, 3042]], &quot;sentence_offsets&quot;: [[0, 24], [25, 61], [62, 105], [106, 120], [121, 255], [256, 371], [372, 487], [488, 617], [618, 791], [792, 943], [944, 1092], [1093, 1184], [1185, 1211], [1212, 1400], [1401, 1530], [1531, 1609], [1610, 1634], [1635, 1733], [1734, 2378], [2379, 2555], [2556, 