<div id="LC11" class="react-code-text react-code-line-contents-no-virtualization react-file-line html-div ">{&quot;document_metadata&quot;: {&quot;document_id&quot;: &quot;16536000&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;overproof-combined&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_filename&quot;: &quot;data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_version&quot;: &quot;v1.0&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_license&quot;: &quot;Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_url&quot;: &quot;https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_doi&quot;: &quot;https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_split&quot;: &quot;all&quot;, &quot;document_type&quot;: &quot;newspaper&quot;, &quot;date&quot;: &quot;1929&quot;, &quot;language&quot;: &quot;en&quot;, &quot;publication_title&quot;: &quot;The Sydney Morn aid&quot;, &quot;transcription_unit_scope&quot;: &quot;article&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_article&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_lines&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_sentences&quot;: &quot;benchmark - automatic&quot;}, &quot;ground_truth&quot;: {&quot;transcription_unit&quot;: &quot;DEATH OF MRS. D. C.\nMcLACHLAN.\nMemories of the days when Darlinghurst\nand Paddington were divided by Boundary\nCreek, and when most of the populous area\nbetween William-street and the harbour was\nheld in Government grants, are recalled by\nthe death on Saturday of Mrs. Emily M.\nMcLachlan, wife of Mr. Duncan Clark\nMcLachlan, C.M.G., I.S.O., of Mosman.\nMrs. McLachlan, was in her 81st year. She\nwas a daughter of the late Mr. Obed West,\nwho inherited Barcom Glen Estate, upon\nwhich much of Darlinghurst and Rushcutter\nBay is built, from his father. The latter\nreceived the estate as a Government grant,\nleaving it to his son In 1810, it was on\nportion of the property, which extended to\nthe water at Rushcutter Bay, that Mrs.\nMcLachlan was born. The estate still re¬\nmains in the West family, of whom two sisters\nand one brother survive, though most of it\nhas been leased. The Rushcutter Bay por¬\ntion was resumed by the Government some\nyears ago.\nMr. McLachlan, who survives his wife, was\nformerly Under-Secretary for Mines and Agri¬\nculture in New South Wales. After Federa¬\ntion he became the first Commonwealth Pub¬\nlic Service Commissioner. He retired from\nthat position in 1916, when he left Melbourne\nto make his home in Mosman. For some years,\ntoo, he was chairman of directors of the\nCivil Service Stores In Sydney.\nThree sons and three daughters also sur¬\nvive. They are Misses Ethel and Thirza\nMcLachlan and Mrs. H. L. Butler, Messrs.\nA. L. and S. C. McLachlan, of Sydney, and\nR. O. McLachlan, of Stockinbingal.\nThe funeral took place yesterday afternoon\nat St. Jude&#39;s Cemetery, Randwick. The prin¬\ncipal mourners were Mr. D. C. McLachlan and\nthe three sons. Mr. A. O. West (brother),\nMr H. L. Butler (son-in-law), and Messrs.\nE. Marriott, H. Ellis. A. Hudson, B. McLach¬\nlan, and H. West (nephews). Others present\nwere Messrs. E. C. Cragen (formerly Com¬\nmonwealth Public Service Inspector for New\nSouth Wales), Duncan (representing the Com¬\nmonwealth Public Service), C. W. Kelety\n(manager) and T. Garratt (director) of the\nCivil Service Stores, and F. A. Coghlan (for¬\nmerly Auditor-General).&quot;, &quot;line_offsets&quot;: [[0, 19], [20, 30], [31, 69], [70, 109], [110, 151], [152, 194], [195, 237], [238, 276], [277, 312], [313, 350], [351, 392], [393, 434], [435, 473], [474, 515], [516, 557], [558, 600], [601, 641], [642, 684], [685, 723], [724, 764], [765, 810], [811, 853], [854, 894], [895, 934], [935, 945], [946, 987], [988, 1032], [1033, 1074], [1075, 1117