<div id="LC24" class="react-code-text react-code-line-contents-no-virtualization react-file-line html-div ">{&quot;document_metadata&quot;: {&quot;document_id&quot;: &quot;sn88074142-11-00280761485-1872040501-1138&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;overproof-combined&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_filename&quot;: &quot;data/03_curated/overproof/dataset3/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_version&quot;: &quot;v1.0&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_license&quot;: &quot;Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.&quot;, &quot;primary_dataset_url&quot;: &quot;https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_name&quot;: &quot;hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_doi&quot;: &quot;https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299&quot;, &quot;benchmark_dataset_split&quot;: &quot;all&quot;, &quot;document_type&quot;: &quot;newspaper&quot;, &quot;date&quot;: &quot;1872&quot;, &quot;language&quot;: &quot;en&quot;, &quot;publication_title&quot;: &quot;THE CARIRO DAILY (ILLINOIS)&quot;, &quot;transcription_unit_scope&quot;: &quot;article&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_article&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_lines&quot;: &quot;primary-dataset - legacy&quot;, &quot;segmentation_origin_sentences&quot;: &quot;benchmark - automatic&quot;}, &quot;ground_truth&quot;: {&quot;transcription_unit&quot;: &quot;A DISCOVERY.\nTHE BODY OF DE SOTO FOUND WHERE IT\nWAS BURIED CENTURIES AGO.\n[From the New Orleans National Republican.]\nOur readers may remember that about\neighteen months ago an article appeared\nin some of our most reliable papers mak¬\ning known some important facts. It stated\nthat Capt. Blank, an old and well-known\nexplorer of our great river and its numer¬\nous tributaries, together with the many bay¬\nous which traverse and intersect our state,\nhad made some interesting discoveries in\nregard to the small islands dotted about\nhere and there in the river and shallow\nlakes of Southern Louisiana.\nAmong the most remarkable of these\nislands noted and explored by Capt. Blank,\nare two not very remote from this city,\nand well-known to all steamboatmen on\nthe river. It seems that Captn. Blank, al¬\nthough so very enterprising and energetic,\nis a man quite advanced in years, being\nnow in his sixty-ninth year. Having\nspent in life on the river since childhood,\nhe remembered that about forty years\nago a fine vessel, hailing from Bordeaux,\nand laden with the best French wines,\nchampagnes, cordials, etc., were sunk at\nor near the spot where one of these is¬\nlands, which had then no existence, now\nstands. This vessel with her cargo was\nowned by parties in France, but was con¬\nsigned to the care of a well-known house\nin New Orleans, which exists still.\nCapt. Blank conceived the idea that this\nvaluable cargo might be rescued from its\nwatery bed by means of diving bells, and\nconsequently he employed several experi¬\nenced divers to examine the wreck and re¬\nport whether it was possible to reach the\nhull of this long sunken vessel.\nThe divers made a thorough examina¬\ntion and reported the plan practicable but\nvery expensive. Capt. Blank applied to\nthe house to whom the vessel had origin¬\nally been consigned and showed the re¬\nport of the divers. This enterprising\nhouse, knowing that a vast fortune would\nreward them if the undertaking was suc¬\ncessful, willingly assisted the captain with\nmen and means to work out his apparently\nwild speculation; and the result has\nproved that wonders will never cease; for\nat last, after more than one year from the\ntime the enterprise was begun, Capt. Blank\nhas really succeeded in raising at least\none-half of the valuable cargo, which has\nbeen sweetening and mellowing beneath\nthe father of waters for nearly a half cen¬\nDuring his researches among the several\nbayous of southern Louisiana, he dis¬\ncovered an island about five miles below\nwhat is known as the \&quot;Old Forts\&quot;, and in\nthe bed of what is termed by steamboat¬\nmen \&quot;Old River.\&quot; This old river was\nonce the natural bed of the Mississippi ;\nbut it cut through a narrow neck of land,\nand formed another outlet. In this\nstream Captain Blank noticed an island,\nwhich he felt convinced was formed over\nsome wreck. One day while wandering\nover it, he discovered beneath the marshy\ngrass something that looked like the bow\nof a boat. He carefully cut away the\nlong tough grass, and we may judge his\nsurprise when he actually made out the\nbow of a boat, apparently in excellent\npreservation. It was strongly built and\ncopper bound, and was an ancient-looking\ncraft. It seemed to rest upon its stern,\nwhich was entirely covered by the soil,\nwhich had accumulated over it, while the\nroots of an immense tree beneath the bow\nwere lifting it from its bed.\nCapt. Blank determined, a few months\nsince, to excavate this ancient craft, or at\nleast what was left of it. The work pro¬\ngressed rapidly with the aid of a power¬\nful dredging machine, and after three\nmonths hard work the Captain had the\nhappiness of reaching the hatchway of the\nhalf-rotten vessel, but day by day passed\nand nothing was brought to light of any\nreal value. A few rusted swords, scab¬\nbards pieces of rusty armor were brought\nup, which being examined by Capt. Blank,\nproved the vessel to have been of Spanish\nbuild. The workmen were disgusted\nwith their useless labor, and had deter¬\nmined to give up their vain enterprise,\nwhen lo! they came upon something\nwhich they firmly believed to be a box of\ngold. Their cupidity and curiosity being\nexcited, they worked hard to raise it from\nits bed of compact mud. Their disgust,\nhowever, was great when the object\nbrought up proved to be a blacksmith&#39;s\nanvil, with Spanish characters wrought\nupon it.\nCapt. Blank, who watched the proceed¬\nings with an eager eye, besought the men\nto continue a few days longer, when at\nlast they came to something which, this\ntime, they felt convinced, was a box of\nMexic gold - perhaps hidden there by\nCapt. Kidd himself. But we may imagine\nthe awe and astonishment of the Captain\nand the workmen when the object was\nraised and cleared of its mud, and laid\nbefore them. It was evidently a human\nbody, completely and perfectly wrapped\nin lead - air and water-tight. Around the\nlead covering was firmly welded a broad\ncopper band with it Spanish inscription,\nrudely wrought upon it, which being\ncleared of its rust and mud, revealed the\nfollowing words :\nAqui ya cen los restos de\nHernando De Soto,\nQue fallecioel dia\n15 de Mayo, de 1542, A. D.,\nde edad de cuarentay cuatro anosy siete\nmesses.\nEach man uncovered his head and re¬\nmained standing in solemn awe as the\nbody was examined. Capt. Blank felt\nconvinced that it was the body of the\ngreat Spaniard, which as every school\nchild knows, was buried in his boat, and\nsunk at midnight in the bosom of the\ngreat Mississippi, to keep the knowledge\nof his death from the Indians, and in all\nprobability the anvil was placed in the\nboat to assist it in settling steadily down.\nThe body of De Soto was brought to the\ncity yesterday, and is now lying in the\nMayor&#39;s parlor at the City Hall. To-mor¬\nrow we learn it will be taken to the\nSchool of Medicine, on Baronne street,\nwhen its leaden wrapping will be removed,\nand in all probability the remains of De¬\nSoto will be laid baree to the reverential\neyes of those who live along the banks of\nthe mighty Mississippi, whose waters have\nat length yielded up the body of its great\ndiscoverer.&quot;, &quot;line_offsets&quot;: [[0, 12], [13, 47], [48, 73], [74, 117], [118, 153], [154, 193], [194, 234], [235, 276], [277, 316], [317, 359], [360, 404], [405, 448], [449, 489], [490, 530], [531, 570], [571, 599], [600, 634], [635, 677], [678, 717], [718, 755], [756, 798